  "ARTICLE_BODY": "Many people believe that a perfectly regular heartbeat is the sign of good health, but medical experts suggest otherwise. Heart Rate Variability (HRV) refers to the slight variations in time between each heartbeat. These tiny fluctuations, measured in milliseconds, actually indicate a healthy cardiovascular system. A heart that beats with perfect regularity might suggest that the nervous system isn't functioning optimally. HRV is controlled by the autonomic nervous system, which manages involuntary bodily functions. Higher HRV generally indicates better cardiovascular fitness, stress resilience, and overall health. Athletes often have higher HRV scores than sedentary individuals. Factors that can negatively impact HRV include chronic stress, poor sleep, excessive alcohol consumption, and lack of physical activity. Modern wearable devices now allow people to monitor their HRV easily. Understanding HRV can help individuals make informed decisions about their lifestyle, training intensity, and recovery needs. Rather than aiming for mechanical regularity, a naturally variable heartbeat reflects the body's ability to adapt and respond to different situations effectively.",
